name: Set
comment:
A collection of objects in which each object can occur only once.

That is, for each object of the element type, the object is either considered to be in the set, or to not be in the set.

Set implementations may consider some elements indistinguishable. These elements are treated as being the same for any operation on the set.

The default dart-core.Set implementation, dart-collection.LinkedHashSet, considers objects indistinguishable if they are equal with regard to operator dart-core.Object.==.

Iterating over elements of a set may be either unordered or ordered in some way. Examples:

  • A dart-collection.HashSet is unordered, which means that its iteration order is uspecified,

  • dart-collection.LinkedHashSet iterates in the insertion order of its elements, and
  • a sorted set like dart-collection.SplayTreeSet iterates the elements in sorted order.

It is generally not allowed to modify the set (add or remove elements) while an operation on the set is being performed, for example during a call to dart-core.IterableBase.forEach or dart-core.Set.containsAll. Nor is it allowed to modify the set while iterating either the set itself or any dart-core.Iterable that is backed by the set, such as the ones returned by methods like dart-core.IterableBase.where and dart-core.IterableBase.map.

iterator.name: iterator
iterator.comment:
Provides an iterator that iterates over the elements of this set.

The order of iteration is defined by the individual Set implementation, but must be consistent between changes to the set.

constructors.comment:
Creates an empty dart-core.Set.

The created dart-core.Set is a plain dart-collection.LinkedHashSet. As such, it considers elements that are equal (using dart-core.Set.==) to be indistinguishable, and requires them to have a compatible dart-core.Set.hashCode implementation.

The set is equivalent to one created by new LinkedHashSet<E>().

from.name: from
from.comment:
Creates a dart-core.Set that contains all elements of dart-core.Set.Set-from.other.

The created dart-core.Set is a dart-collection.LinkedHashSet. As such, it considers elements that are equal (using dart-core.Set.==) to be undistinguishable, and requires them to have a compatible dart-core.Set.hashCode implementation.

The set is equivalent to one created by new LinkedHashSet<E>.from(other).

identity.name: identity
identity.comment:
Creates an empty identity dart-core.Set.

The created dart-core.Set is a dart-collection.LinkedHashSet that uses identity as equality relation.

The set is equivalent to one created by new LinkedHashSet<E>.identity().

add.name: add
add.comment:
Adds dart-core.Set.add.value into the set. Returns true if dart-core.Set.add.value was added to the set.

If dart-core.Set.add.value already exists, the set is not changed and false is returned.

addAll.name: addAll
addAll.comment:
Adds all of dart-core.Set.addAll.elements to this Set.

Equivalent to adding each element in dart-core.Set.addAll.elements using dart-core.Set.add, but some collections may be able to optimize it.

contains.name: contains
contains.comment: Returns true if dart-core.Set.contains.value is in the set.

containsAll.name: containsAll
containsAll.comment: Returns whether this Set contains all the elements of dart-core.Set.containsAll.other.

difference.name: difference
difference.comment:
Returns a new set with the the elements of this that are not in dart-core.Set.difference.other.

That is, the returned set contains all the elements of this dart-core.Set that are not elements of dart-core.Set.difference.other according to other.contains.

intersection.name: intersection
intersection.comment:
Returns a new set which is the intersection between this set and dart-core.Set.intersection.other.

That is, the returned set contains all the elements of this dart-core.Set that are also elements of dart-core.Set.intersection.other according to other.contains.

lookup.name: lookup
lookup.comment:
If an object equal to dart-core.Set.lookup.object is in the set, return it.

Checks if there is an object in the set that is equal to dart-core.Set.lookup.object. If so, that object is returned, otherwise returns null.

remove.name: remove
remove.comment: Removes dart-core.Set.remove.value from the set. Returns true if dart-core.Set.remove.value was in the set. Returns false otherwise. The method has no effect if dart-core.Set.remove.value value was not in the set.

removeAll.name: removeAll
removeAll.comment: Removes each element of dart-core.Set.removeAll.elements from this set.

removeWhere.name: removeWhere
removeWhere.comment: Removes all elements of this set that satisfy dart-core.Set.removeWhere.test.

retainAll.name: retainAll
retainAll.comment:
Removes all elements of this set that are not elements in dart-core.Set.retainAll.elements.

Checks for each element of dart-core.Set.retainAll.elements whether there is an element in this set that is equal to it (according to this.contains), and if so, the equal element in this set is retained, and elements that are not equal to any element in elements are removed.

retainWhere.name: retainWhere
retainWhere.comment: Removes all elements of this set that fail to satisfy dart-core.Set.retainWhere.test.

union.name: union
union.comment:
Returns a new set which contains all the elements of this set and dart-core.Set.union.other.

That is, the returned set contains all the elements of this dart-core.Set and all the elements of dart-core.Set.union.other.

first.name: first
first.comment:
Returns the first element.

If this is empty throws a dart-core.StateError. Otherwise this method is equivalent to this.elementAt(0)

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides dart-core.Set.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

isEmpty.name: isEmpty
isEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is no element in this collection.

isNotEmpty.name: isNotEmpty
isNotEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is at least one element in this collection.

iterator.name: iterator
iterator.comment: Returns an Iterator that iterates over this Iterable object.

last.name: last
last.comment:
Returns the last element.

If this is empty throws a dart-core.StateError.

length.name: length
length.comment:
Returns the number of elements in the iterable.

This is an efficient operation that doesn't require iterating through the elements.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

single.name: single
single.comment:
Returns the single element in this.

If this is empty or has more than one element throws a dart-core.StateError.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and dart-core.Set.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the dart-core.Set.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

any.name: any
any.comment: Returns true if one element of this collection satisfies the predicate test. Returns false otherwise.

contains.name: contains
contains.comment: Returns true if the collection contains an element equal to dart-core.Set.contains.element.

elementAt.name: elementAt
elementAt.comment:
Returns the dart-core.Set.elementAt.indexth element.

The dart-core.Set.elementAt.index must be non-negative and less than dart-core.Set.length.

Note: if this does not have a deterministic iteration order then the function may simply return any element without any iteration if there are at least dart-core.Set.elementAt.index elements in this.

every.name: every
every.comment: Returns true if every elements of this collection satisify the predicate test. Returns false otherwise.

expand.name: expand
expand.comment:
Expands each element of this dart-core.Iterable into zero or more elements.

The resulting Iterable runs through the elements returned by dart-core.Set.expand.f for each element of this, in order.

The returned dart-core.Iterable is lazy, and calls dart-core.Set.expand.f for each element of this every time it's iterated.

firstWhere.name: firstWhere
firstWhere.comment:
Returns the first element that satisfies the given predicate dart-core.Set.firstWhere.test.

If none matches, the result of invoking the dart-core.Set.firstWhere.orElse function is returned. By default, when dart-core.Set.firstWhere.orElse is null, a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

fold.name: fold
fold.comment:
Reduces a collection to a single value by iteratively combining each element of the collection with an existing value using the provided function.

Use dart-core.Set.fold.initialValue as the initial value, and the function dart-core.Set.fold.combine to create a new value from the previous one and an element.

Example of calculating the sum of an iterable:

iterable.fold(0, (prev, element) => prev + element);

forEach.name: forEach
forEach.comment: Applies the function dart-core.Set.forEach.f to each element of this collection.

join.name: join
join.comment:
Converts each element to a dart-core.String and concatenates the strings.

Converts each element to a dart-core.String by calling dart-core.Set.toString on it. Then concatenates the strings, optionally separated by the dart-core.Set.join.separator string.

lastWhere.name: lastWhere
lastWhere.comment:
Returns the last element that satisfies the given predicate dart-core.Set.lastWhere.test.

If none matches, the result of invoking the dart-core.Set.lastWhere.orElse function is returned. By default, when dart-core.Set.lastWhere.orElse is null, a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

map.name: map
map.comment:
Returns a lazy dart-core.Iterable where each element e of this is replaced by the result of f(e).

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the returned dart-core.Iterable is not iterated over, the supplied function dart-core.Set.map.f will not be invoked. The transformed elements will not be cached. Iterating multiple times over the the returned dart-core.Iterable will invoke the supplied function dart-core.Set.map.f multiple times on the same element.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
dart-core.Set.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to dart-core.Set.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If dart-core.Set.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of dart-core.Set.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

reduce.name: reduce
reduce.comment:
Reduces a collection to a single value by iteratively combining elements of the collection using the provided function.

Example of calculating the sum of an iterable:

iterable.reduce((value, element) => value + element);

singleWhere.name: singleWhere
singleWhere.comment: Returns the single element that satisfies dart-core.Set.singleWhere.test. If no or more than one element match then a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

skip.name: skip
skip.comment:
Returns an Iterable that skips the first dart-core.Set.skip.n elements.

If this has fewer than dart-core.Set.skip.n elements, then the resulting Iterable is empty.

It is an error if dart-core.Set.skip.n is negative.

skipWhile.name: skipWhile
skipWhile.comment:
Returns an Iterable that skips elements while dart-core.Set.skipWhile.test is satisfied.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new Iterator of the returned Iterable iterates over all elements of this.

As long as the iterator's elements satisfy dart-core.Set.skipWhile.test they are discarded. Once an element does not satisfy the dart-core.Set.skipWhile.test the iterator stops testing and uses every later element unconditionally. That is, the elements of the returned Iterable are the elements of this starting from the first element that does not satisfy dart-core.Set.skipWhile.test.

take.name: take
take.comment:
Returns an dart-core.Iterable with at most dart-core.Set.take.n elements.

The returned dart-core.Iterable may contain fewer than dart-core.Set.take.n elements, if this contains fewer than dart-core.Set.take.n elements.

It is an error if dart-core.Set.take.n is negative.

takeWhile.name: takeWhile
takeWhile.comment:
Returns an Iterable that stops once dart-core.Set.takeWhile.test is not satisfied anymore.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new Iterator of the returned Iterable starts iterating over the elements of this.

When the iterator encounters an element e that does not satisfy dart-core.Set.takeWhile.test, it discards e and moves into the finished state. That is, it does not get or provide any more elements.

toList.name: toList
toList.comment:
Creates a dart-core.List containing the elements of this dart-core.Iterable.

The elements are in iteration order. The list is fixed-length if dart-core.Set.toList.growable is false.

toSet.name: toSet
toSet.comment: Creates a dart-core.Set containing the elements of this dart-core.Iterable.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

where.name: where
where.comment:
Returns a lazy dart-core.Iterable with all elements that satisfy the predicate test.

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the returned dart-core.Iterable is not iterated over, the supplied function test will not be invoked. Iterating will not cache results, and thus iterating multiple times over the returned dart-core.Iterable will invoke the supplied function test multiple times on the same element.
